# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both the mushers and their dogs were portrayed as heroes in the newly popular medium of radio and received headline coverage in newspapers across the United States.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto, the lead sled dog on the final stretch into Nome, became the most famous canine celebrity of the era after Rin Tin Tin, and his statue is a popular tourist attraction in both New York City's Central Park and downtown Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's team covered much of the most dangerous parts of the route and ran the farthest: Togo's team covered 261 miles (420 km) while Balto's team ran 55 miles (89 km).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From November to July, the port on the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula of the Bering Sea was icebound and inaccessible by steamship.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only link to the rest of the world during the winter was the Iditarod Trail, which ran 938 miles (1,510 km) from the port of Seward in the south, across several mountain ranges and the vast Alaska Interior, to the town of Nome.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In Alaska and other subarctic regions, the primary source of mail and needed supplies in 1925 was the dog sled.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Within a decade, bush flying became the dominant method of transportation during the winter months.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the winter of 1924–1925, Curtis Welch was the only doctor in Nome.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He and four nurses, working at the small Maynard Columbus Hospital, served the town and the surrounding area.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After discovering the hospital's entire batch of diphtheria antitoxin had expired, Welch placed an order for more.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] However, the replacement shipment did not arrive before the port was closed by ice for the winter, and more could not be shipped in to Nome until spring.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the next few weeks, after the number of cases grew and four children were dead—whom Welch had not been able to autopsy—he became increasingly concerned about diphtheria.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By mid-January 1925, Welch officially diagnosed the first case of diphtheria in a three-year-old boy who died only two weeks after first becoming ill.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, when a seven-year-old girl presented the same symptoms of diphtheria, Welch attempted to administer some of the expired antitoxin to see if it might still have any effect, but the girl died a few hours later.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Realizing that an epidemic was imminent, Welch called Nome's mayor, George Maynard, that same evening to arrange an emergency town council meeting.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The council immediately implemented a quarantine.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, on January 22, 1925, Welch sent radio telegrams to all other major towns in Alaska alerting them of the public health risk.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also requested assistance from the U.S.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite the quarantine, there were over 20 confirmed cases of diphtheria and at least 50 more at risk by the end of January.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Without antitoxin, it was expected that in the surrounding region's population of around 10,000 people, the mortality rate could be close to 100 percent.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A previous influenza pandemic had hit the area in 1918, causing fatalities in about 50 percent of the native population of Nome and 8% of the native population of Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More than 1,000 people died in northwest Alaska, and approximately 2,000 across the state.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority were Alaska Natives who did not have any resistance to either disease.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At the January 24 meeting of the board of health, superintendent Mark Summers of the Hammon Consolidated Gold Fields proposed a dogsled relay using two fast teams.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] One would start at Nenana, Alaska, the closest railhead on the Alaska Railroad, and the other at Nome, and they would meet roughly halfway in the town of Nulato.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The trip from Nulato to Nome normally took 30 days.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Curtis Welch estimated that the serum would last only six days under the brutal conditions of the trail.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers's employee, the Norwegian sled dog trainer and musher Leonhard Seppala, was chosen for the 630-mile (1,014 km) round trip from Nome to Nulato and back.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He had previously made the run in a record-breaking four days, won the All-Alaska Sweepstakes three times, and had become famous for his athletic ability and rapport with his Siberian huskies.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] His lead dog, the 12-year-old Togo, was equally famous for his leadership, intelligence, and ability to sense danger.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard proposed flying the antitoxin by plane.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1925, planes were a relatively new technology, and Alaska's harsh winter weather made them unreliable.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Several test flights had been conducted the previous year between Fairbanks and McGrath, Alaska, to determine how well a reliable aircraft could handle the winter conditions.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The longest test flight flew a distance of only 260 miles (420 km), a little under half the necessary distance between Nenana and Nome.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only planes operating in Alaska in 1925 were three vintage biplanes, which had been dismantled for the winter.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Their open cockpits and water-cooled engines would make these planes unfit for the trip as well.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Although it was potentially quicker, the proposal to deliver the antitoxin by flight was rejected by the board of health.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Instead, they voted unanimously for the dogsled relay.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was notified that evening and immediately began preparations for the trip.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Public Health Service had located 1.1 million units of serum in West Coast hospitals which could be shipped to Seattle, Washington, and then transported to Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The next ship north would not arrive in Seattle until January 31, and it would take another six to seven days to arrive in Seward.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 26, 300,000 forgotten units of the antitoxin were located in a hospital in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The supply was wrapped in glass vials, then padded quilts, and finally a metallic cylinder weighing a little over 20 pounds (9 kg).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At Governor Scott Bone's order, it was immediately shipped to Nenana and arrived the next day.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While not sufficient to defeat the epidemic, the 300,000 units could slow the spread of the disease until the larger shipment arrived.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail route from Nenana to Nome spanned 674 miles (1,085 km) in total.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] It crossed the barren Alaska Interior, following the Tanana River for 137 miles (220 km) to the village Tanana at the junction with the Yukon River, and then following the Yukon for 230 miles (370 km) to Kaltag.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then passed west 90 miles (140 km) over the Kaltag Portage to Unalakleet on the shore of Norton Sound.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then continued for 208 miles (335 km) northwest around the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula with no protection from gales and blizzards, including a 42-mile (68 km) stretch across the shifting ice of the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Edward Wetzler, the US Postal Service inspector for Nenana, contacted Tom Parson, an agent of the Northern Commercial Company, contracted to deliver mail between Fairbanks and Unalakleet.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Telephones and telegraphs turned the drivers back to their assigned roadhouses.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail carriers held a revered position in the territory, and were the best dog mushers in Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority of relay drivers across the Interior were native Athabaskans, direct descendants of the original dog mushers.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The first musher in the relay was "Wild Bill" Shannon, who was handed the 20 pounds (9 kg) package at the train station in Nenana on January 27 at 9:00 pm AKST by night.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite a temperature of −50 °F (−46 °C), Shannon left immediately with his team of 9 inexperienced dogs, led by Blackie.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature began to drop, and the team was forced onto the colder ice of the river because the trail had been destroyed by horses.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite jogging alongside the sled to keep warm, Shannon developed hypothermia.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He reached Minto at 3 am, with parts of his face black from frostbite.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum by the fire and resting for four hours, Shannon dropped three dogs and left with the remaining 8.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The three dogs died shortly after Shannon returned for them, and a fourth may have died as well.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Half-Athabaskan Edgar Kalland arrived in Minto the night before, and was sent back to Tolovana, traveling 70 mi (110 km) the day before the relay.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shannon and his team arrived in bad condition at 11 am, and handed over the serum.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum in the roadhouse, Kalland headed into the forest.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had fallen to −56 °F (−49 °C), causing Kalland's hands to freeze to the sled's handlebar, requiring the owner of the Manley Hot Springs roadhouse to pour boiling water on the birch wood bar for thawing.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No new cases of diphtheria were diagnosed on January 28, but two new cases were diagnosed on January 29.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The quarantine had been obeyed, but lack of diagnostic tools and the contagiousness of the strain rendered it ineffective.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More units of serum were discovered around Juneau the same day.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While no count exists, the estimate based on weight is roughly 125,000 units, enough to treat 4 to 6 patients.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The crisis had become headline news in newspapers, including in San Francisco, Cleveland, Washington D.C., and New York, and spread to the radio sets which were just becoming common.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The storm system from Alaska hit the contiguous United States, bringing record lows to New York, and freezing the Hudson River.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard and Alaskan House Delegate Daniel Sutherland renewed their campaign for flying the remaining serum by plane.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Different proposals included flying a large aircraft 2,000 miles (3,200 km) from Seattle to Nome, carrying a plane to the edge of the pack ice via Navy ship and launching it, and the original plan of flying the serum from Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite receiving headline coverage across the country and support from Arctic explorer Roald Amundsen, the plans were rejected by experienced pilots, the Navy, and Governor Bone.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As publisher and editor of the *Fairbanks Daily News-Miner* newspaper, William Fentress Thompson harshly criticized government officials for inaction and funded a private fleet of planes.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In response, Governor Bone decided to speed up the relay, authorizing additional drivers for Seppala's leg of the relay, so they could travel without rest.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was still scheduled to cover the most dangerous leg, the shortcut across Norton Sound, but the telephone and telegraph systems bypassed the small villages he was passing through, and there was no way to tell him to wait at Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plan relied on the driver from the north catching Seppala on the trail.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers arranged for drivers along the last leg, including Seppala's colleague Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From Manley Hot Springs, the serum passed through largely Athabascan hands before George Nollner delivered it to Charlie Evans at Bishop Mountain on January 30 at 3 am.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had warmed slightly, but at −62 °F (−52 °C), was dropping again.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Evans relied on his lead dogs when he passed through ice fog where the Koyukuk River, flowing into the Yukon, had broken through and surged over the ice, but forgot to protect the groins of his two short-haired mixed breed lead dogs with rabbit skins.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both dogs collapsed with frostbite, with Evans having to take their place himself pulling the sled.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at 10 am; both dogs were dead.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Tommy Patsy departed within half an hour.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The transport of the serum then parted ways with the Yukon River as the river turned south and the trail crossed the Kaltag Portage west to the coast.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gonangnan saw the signs of a storm brewing, and decided not to take the shortcut across the dangerous ice of the Sound.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was not there, but Henry Ivanoff was waiting just in case.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 30, the number of cases in Nome had reached 27 and the antitoxin was depleted.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to a reporter living in Nome, "All hope is in the dogs and their heroic drivers ...
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nome appears to be a deserted city." With the report of Gonangnan's progress on January 31, Welch believed the serum would arrive there in February.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Leonhard Seppala and his dog sled team, with his lead dog Togo, travelled 91 miles (146 km) from Nome from January 27 to January 31 into the oncoming storm.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They took the shortcut across the Norton Sound, and headed toward Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature in Nome was a relatively warm −20 °F (−29 °C), but in Shaktoolik, the temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), and the gale force winds causing a wind chill of −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Henry Ivanoff's team ran into a reindeer and got tangled up just outside Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala still believed he had more than 100 mi (160 km) to the original relay point in Nulato to go and had raced to get off the Norton Sound before the storm hit.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was passing the team when Ivanoff shouted, "The serum!
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala turned around with the serum but it was dark by the time he got to Ungalik.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] But with the news of the worsening epidemic Ivanoff had shared, he decided not to stop and once again set out to brave the storm across the 20 miles (32 km) of exposed open ice of the Norton Sound.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), but the wind chill with the gale force winds was −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo led the team in a straight line through the dark, and they arrived at the roadhouse in Isaac's Point on the other side at 8 pm.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In one day, they had travelled 84 mi (135 km), averaging 8 mph (13 km/h).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The team rested, and departed at 2 am into the full power of the storm.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] During the night, the temperature dropped to −40 °F (−40 °C), and the wind increased to storm force (at least 65 mph [105 km/h]).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While they slept, it had blown out to sea all the ice Seppala had just crossed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There was still some ice close to shore for the next part of their journey along the coast, but it was rough and starting to break up too.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They stuck close to shore, and Togo picked his way carefully until they were back on solid ground.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Next they had to cross Little McKinley Mountain (1,200 feet [370 m]), another of the toughest parts of the trail because of the many up-and-down ridges.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The total elevation climbed in that section of over 8 miles (13 km) is 5,000 feet (1,500 m).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After descending to the next roadhouse in Golovin, Seppala passed the serum to Charlie Olsen on February 1 at 3 pm.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 1, the number of cases in Nome rose to 28.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum en route was sufficient to treat 30 people.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With the powerful blizzard raging and winds of 80 mph (130 km/h), Welch ordered a stop to the relay until the storm passed, reasoning that a delay was better than the risk of losing all the serum.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Messages were left at Solomon and Point Safety before the lines went dead.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olsen was blown off the trail, and suffered severe frostbite in his hands while putting blankets on his dogs.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at Bluff on February 1 at 7 pm in poor condition.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen waited until 10 pm for the storm to break, but it only got worse and the drifts would soon block the trail, so he departed into a headwind.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen traveled through the night, through drifts, and river overflow over the 600-foot (183 m) Topkok Mountain.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto led the team through visibility so poor that Kaasen could not always see the dogs harnessed closest to the sled.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was two miles (3 km) past Solomon before he realized it, and kept going.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The winds after Solomon were so severe that his sled flipped over and he almost lost the cylinder containing the serum when it fell off and became buried in the snow.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also suffered frostbite when he had to use his bare hands to feel for the cylinder.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen reached Point Safety ahead of schedule on February 2, at 3 am.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn believed that Kaasen and the relay had halted at Solomon, so he was sleeping.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Since the weather was improving, it would take time to prepare Rohn's team, and Balto and the other dogs were moving well, Kaasen pressed on with the remaining 25 miles (40 km) to Nome, reaching Front Street at 5:30 am.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Not a single ampule was broken, and the antitoxin was thawed and ready by noon.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Together, the teams covered the 674 miles (1,085 km) in 1271⁄2 hours, which was considered a world record, done in extreme subzero temperatures in near-blizzard conditions and hurricane-force winds.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Margaret Curran from the Solomon Roadhouse was infected, which raised fears that the disease might spread from patrons of the roadhouse to other communities.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1.1 million units had left Seattle on January 31, and were not due by dog sled until February 8.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Welch asked for half the serum to be delivered by aircraft from Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He contacted Thompson and Sutherland, and Darling made a test flight the next morning.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With his health advisor, Governor Bone concluded the cases in Nome were actually going down, and withheld permission, but preparations went ahead.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Navy moved a minesweeper north from Seattle, and the Signal Corps were ordered to light fires to guide the planes.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By February 3, the original 300,000 units had proved to be still effective, and the epidemic was under control.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A sixth death, probably unrelated to diphtheria, was widely reported as a new outbreak of the disease.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The batch from Seattle arrived on board the *Admiral Watson* on February 7.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Acceding to pressure, Governor Bone authorized half to be delivered by plane.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 8, the first half of the second shipment began its trip by dog sled, while the plane failed to start when a broken radiator shutter caused the engine to overheat.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plane failed the next day as well, and the mission was scrapped.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Thompson was gracious in his editorials.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The second relay included many of the same drivers, and also faced harsh conditions.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn delivered the serum to Nome during another blizzard after a 90 miles (140 km) run on February 15.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The death toll from diphtheria in Nome is officially listed as either 5, 6, or 7, but Welch later estimated there were probably at least 100 additional cases among "the Eskimo camps outside the city.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Natives have a habit of burying their children without reporting the death." Forty-three new cases were diagnosed in 1926, but they were easily managed with the fresh supply of serum.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] All participants in the dogsleds received letters of commendation from President Calvin Coolidge, and the Senate stopped work to recognize the event.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Each musher during the first relay received a gold medal from the H.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mayor of Los Angeles presented a bone-shaped key to the city to Balto in front of City Hall and silent-film actress Mary Pickford put a wreath around the canine's neck.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Poems and letters from children poured in, and spontaneous fundraising campaigns sprang up around the country.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen and his team became celebrities and toured the West Coast from February 1925 to February 1926, and also starred in a 30-minute film entitled *Balto's Race to Nome*.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A statue of Balto by sculptor Frederick Roth was unveiled in New York City's Central Park during a visit on December 15, 1925.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto and the other dogs later became part of a sideshow and lived in horrible conditions until they were rescued by George Kimble, who organized a fundraising campaign by the children of Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On March 19, 1927, the dogs received a hero's welcome as they arrived at their permanent home at the Cleveland Zoo.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because of his age, Balto was euthanized on March 14, 1933, at the age of 14.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was mounted and placed on display in the Cleveland Museum of Natural History.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In October 1926, Seppala took Togo and his team on a tour from Seattle to California, and then across the Midwest to New England, and consistently drew huge crowds.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They were featured at Madison Square Garden in New York City for 10 days, and Togo received a gold medal from Roald Amundsen.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In New England, Seppala's team of Siberians ran in many races, easily defeating the local Chinooks of Arthur Walden.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala entered into a partnership with Elizabeth M.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ricker in Poland Spring, Maine, where many of his dogs went to live in retirement and contribute to their breeding program of Siberian sled dogs, including Togo, who sired many litters.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala visited Togo, and was by his side when he was euthanized on December 5, 1929, at the age of 16.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After his death, Seppala had Togo preserved and mounted, and today the dog is on display in a glass case at the Iditarod museum in Wasilla, Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's prowess as a sled dog also led to his strengths being preserved through breeding, with his descendants contributing to the "Seppala Siberian Sleddog", a sought after working sled dog line, as well as the mainstream show-stock Siberian Husky gene pool.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] None of the other mushers received the same degree of attention, though Wild Bill Shannon briefly toured with Blackie.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The media largely ignored the Alaska Native mushers, who covered two-thirds of the distance to Nome.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum race helped spur the Air Mail Act of 1925, which was signed into law on February 2.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The bill allowed private aviation companies to bid on mail delivery contracts.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Technology improved and, within a decade, air mail routes were established in Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The last mail delivery by private dog sled under contract took place in 1938, and the last U.S.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Post Office dog sled route closed in 1963.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Dog sledding remained popular in the rural interior but became nearly extinct when snowmobiles spread in the 1960s.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushing was revitalized as a recreational sport in the 1970s with the immense popularity of the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, which runs more than 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from Anchorage to Nome, is based on the All-Alaska Sweepstakes, it has many traditions that commemorate the race to deliver the serum to Nome, especially Seppala and Togo.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The honorary musher for the first seven races was Leonhard Seppala.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Other serum run participants, including "Wild Bill" Shannon, Edgar Kalland, Bill McCarty, Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, Harry Pitka, and Henry Ivanoff have also been honored.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 2005 Iditarod honored Jirdes Winther Baxter, the last known survivor of the epidemic.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The position is now known as Leonhard Seppala's Honorary Musher, the Leonhard Seppala Humanitarian Award is given to the musher who provides the best dog care while remaining competitive, and the Leonhard Seppala Heritage Grant is an Iditarod scholarship.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The two races follow the same route from Ruby to Nome.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A reenactment of the serum run was held in 1975, which took six days longer than the 1925 serum run, or more than twice the total time.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Many of the participants were descendants of the original 20.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1985, President Ronald Reagan sent a letter of recognition to Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, and Bill McCarty, the only remaining survivors.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nollner was the last to die, on January 18, 1999, of a heart attack.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The relay has been depicted in various media.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shortly before World War II, Czech teacher and writer František Omelka was fascinated by the story, writing the novella *Štafeta* ("Relay") published in Czech in 1946.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As an avid Esperantist, Omelka himself translated it into Esperanto, with subsequent translations into German, Dutch, Frisian, Icelandic, Chinese, Japanese, and English.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum run was featured in the 1949 animated short "Daffy Duck Hunt", where Daffy Duck describes his time in a freezer as though he were delivering serum on a dog sled.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1976, the story was retold in *Race Against Death: A True Story of the Far North,* by children's author Seymour Reit.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Reit's book was featured in a 1978 episode of *The Book Bird*, a PBS program where host John Robbins illustrated key scenes from the book being discussed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1995 2D hand-drawn animated film *Balto* with music composed by James Roy Horner was loosely based on the events of the final leg of the serum run, although all of the characters besides Balto are fictional for family and children entertainments.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 2013, a documentary titled *Icebound – The Greatest Dog Story Ever Told*, focused on the aftermath of the events.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *The Great Alaskan Race*, a 2019 film, produced by Rebel Road Entertainment, is based on the serum run.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *Togo*, produced by Walt Disney Pictures, debuted on December 20, 2019, on Disney+.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There is much controversy surrounding Balto's role in the serum run and the statue in Central Park.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He then handed the serum off to Charlie Olson.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olson carried it 25 miles (40 km) to Bluff where he turned it over to Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen was supposed to hand off the serum to Rohn at Port Safety, but Rohn had gone to sleep and Kaasen decided to keep going to Nome.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In all, Kaasen and Balto ran a total of 53 miles (85 km).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to Togo's musher, Leonhard Seppala, who was also Balto's owner, Balto was a scrub freight dog that he left behind when he set out on the trip.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also asserted that Kaasen's lead dog was actually a dog named Fox, but that news agents of the time thought that Balto was a more newsworthy name.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No record exists of Seppala ever having used Balto as a leader in runs or races prior to 1925, and Seppala himself stated Balto "was never in a winning team".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because the pictures and video of Kaasen and Balto taken in Nome were recreated hours after their arrival once the sun had risen, speculation still exists as to whether Balto's position as lead dog was genuine, or was staged or exaggerated for media purposes.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Central Park statue of Balto was modeled after Balto, but shows him wearing Togo's colors (awards).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Katy Steinmetz, writing in *Time* magazine, also thought that Togo was the greatest sled dog of all time.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushers (in order) and the distances they covered.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Most legs were planned to be about 25 miles (40 km) long, generally accepted as an "extreme day's mush".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The **1964 Alaska earthquake**, also known as the **Great Alaska earthquake** and **Good Friday earthquake**, occurred at 5:36 PM AKST on Good Friday, March 27, 1964.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Across south-central Alaska, ground fissures, collapsing structures, and tsunamis resulting from the earthquake caused about 139 deaths.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Lasting four minutes and thirty-eight seconds, the magnitude 9.2–9.3 megathrust earthquake remains the most powerful earthquake ever recorded in North America and the second most powerful earthquake ever recorded in the world since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other man-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The survivors outran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] UTC), a fault between the Pacific and North American plates ruptured near College Fjord in Prince William Sound.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The epicenter of the earthquake was 12.4 mi (20.0 km) north of Prince William Sound, 78 miles (126 km) east of Anchorage and 40 miles (64 km) west of Valdez.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The focus occurred at a depth of approximately 15.5 mi (24.9 km).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Ocean floor shifts created large tsunamis (up to 220 feet (67 m) in height), which resulted in many of the deaths and much of the property damage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The earthquake also caused large rockslides, resulting in great property damage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Vertical displacement of up to 38 feet (12 m) occurred, affecting an area of 100,000 square miles (260,000 km2) within Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Studies of ground motion have led to a peak ground acceleration estimate of 0.14–0.18 *g*.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The earthquake was assigned a maximum Modified Mercalli intensity of X (*Extreme*).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Shaking was felt across much of Alaska and parts of western Yukon and British Columbia in Canada.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The Alaska earthquake was a subduction zone (megathrust) earthquake, caused by an oceanic plate sinking under a continental plate.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The fault responsible was the Aleutian Megathrust, a reverse fault caused by a compressional force.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] This caused much of the uneven ground, the result of shifting to the opposite elevation.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Uplift occurred across 520,000 km2 (200,000 sq mi) from southern Kodiak to Prince William Sound and further east of the sound.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The maximum uplift was in Montague Island, where the ground was raised 13–15 m (43–49 ft) relative to sea level.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The uplift also affected Kodiak, Sitkalidak, and Sitkinak islands.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Subsidence was observed for 285,000 km2 (110,000 sq mi) from north and west of the sound, in Chugach Mountains, most of Kenai Peninsula, and almost all the Kodiak Island group.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Two types of tsunami were produced by this subduction zone earthquake.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] There was a tectonic tsunami produced in addition to about 20 smaller and local tsunamis.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] These smaller tsunamis were produced by submarine and subaerial landslides and were responsible for the majority of the tsunami damage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Tsunami waves were noted in over 20 countries, including Peru, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, Japan, Mexico, and in the continent of Antarctica.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The largest tsunami wave was recorded in Shoup Bay, near Valdez, Alaska, with a height of about 220 ft (67 m).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] As a result of the earthquake, 139 people are believed to have died: Fifteen died as a result of the earthquake itself and another 124 died from the subsequent tsunamis in Alaska, Oregon, and California.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Five died from the tsunami in Oregon, and 13 died from the tsunami in California, mostly in or near Crescent City.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Property damage was estimated at $116 million ($894 million in 2024 dollars).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Most damage occurred in Anchorage, 75 mi (121 km) northwest of the epicenter.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Anchorage was not hit by tsunamis, but downtown Anchorage was heavily damaged, and parts of the city built on sandy bluffs overlying "Bootlegger Cove clay" near Cook Inlet, most notably the Turnagain neighborhood, suffered landslide damage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The neighborhood lost 75 houses in the landslide, and the destroyed area has since been turned into Earthquake Park.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The Government Hill school suffered from the Government Hill landslide, leaving it in two jagged, broken pieces.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Land overlooking the Ship Creek valley near the Alaska Railroad yards also slid, destroying many acres of buildings and city blocks in downtown Anchorage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Most other areas of the city were only moderately damaged.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The concrete control tower at Anchorage International Airport collapsed, killing the controller on the top floor, as well as trapping two cooks on the first floor, who were later rescued.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] 10th Avenue suffered peripheral damage, but only one block away the recently completed (and still unoccupied) Four Seasons Building on Ninth Avenue collapsed completely, with the concrete elevator shafts sticking up out of the rubble like a seesaw.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The hamlets of Girdwood and Portage, located 30 and 40 mi (48 and 64 km) southeast of central Anchorage on the Turnagain Arm, were destroyed by subsidence and subsequent tidal action.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Girdwood was relocated inland and Portage was abandoned.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] About 20 miles (32 km) of the Seward Highway sank below the high-water mark of Turnagain Arm; the highway and its bridges were raised and rebuilt in 1964–66.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Most coastal towns in the Prince William Sound, Kenai Peninsula, and Kodiak Island areas, especially the major ports of Seward, Whittier and Kodiak were heavily damaged by a combination of seismic activity, subsidence, post-quake tsunamis and/or earthquake-caused fires.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Valdez with 32 dead was not totally destroyed, but after three years, the town relocated to higher ground four miles (6.4 km) west of its original site.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Some Alaska Native villages, including Chenega and Afognak, were destroyed or damaged.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The earthquake caused the ballistic missile detection radar of Clear Air Force Station to go offline for six minutes, the only unscheduled interruption in its operational history.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Near Cordova, the Million Dollar Bridge crossing the Copper River also suffered damage, with Span #4 slipping off its pylon and collapsing.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The community of Girdwood was also confined to the southern side of the Seward Highway when water rushed into Turnagain Arm and flooded or destroyed any buildings left standing to the north of the highway.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Only the ground immediately along the highway and that on the north side of the road dropped, prompting geologists to speculate that Girdwood may rest upon an ancient cliff face covered by thousands of years of sediment and glacial deposits.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] A 4.5 ft (1.4 m) wave reached Prince Rupert, British Columbia, just south of the Alaska Panhandle, about three hours after the earthquake.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The tsunami then reached Tofino, on the exposed west coast of Vancouver Island, and traveled up a fjord to hit Port Alberni twice, washing away 55 homes and damaging 375 others.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The towns of Hot Springs Cove, Zeballos, and Amai also saw damage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The damage in British Columbia was estimated at CA$10 million ($100 million in 2025 Canadian dollars or $96 million in 2025 US dollars).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Ten people were killed by the tsunami in Crescent City, California, and one other man was killed near Requa, California after being swept out to sea while fishing in the Klamath River.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Four children were killed while camping with their parents on the Oregon coast at Beverly Beach State Park.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] An additional death that is sometimes attributed to the tsunami took place in Bolinas, California; a fisherman wading into a seaside channel at Duxbury Point was swept into the ocean by a strong surge that took place 13 hours after the initial tidal surge.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Crescent City was particularly hard-hit, with 30 blocks destroyed, representing half of the city's waterfront business district.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The total damage to Crescent City was estimated at $7.4 million ($76 million in 2025 dollars).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Other coastal towns and harbors in the Pacific Northwest, California, and Hawaii were damaged, often extensively.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Damage to harbors and boats occurred as far south as Long Beach, California.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Effects of the earthquake were even noted as far east as Freeport, Texas, where tide gauges recorded waves similar to seismic surface waves.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Seiches were detected in wells in countries around the world, including England, Namibia, and Australia.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] There were hundreds of aftershocks in the first weeks following the main shock.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] In the first day alone, eleven major aftershocks with a magnitude greater than 6.0 were recorded.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Nine more struck over the next three weeks.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] In all, thousands of aftershocks occurred in the months following the quake, and smaller aftershocks continued to strike the region for more than a year.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before, and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Dr.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Broadcast journalist Genie Chance assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction and financially supported the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of significant oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1964-alaska-earthquake] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard established the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The **1966 Georgia gubernatorial election** was held in the U.S. state on November 8, 1966.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] After an election that exposed divisions within the Georgia Democratic Party (giving the Georgia Republican Party a shot at the Governor's Mansion for the first time in the twentieth century), segregationist Democrat Lester Maddox was elected Governor of Georgia.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The voting also brought future President Jimmy Carter to statewide prominence for the first time.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The election was the closest in Georgia gubernatorial history; Republican candidate Bo Callaway won a plurality of the popular vote, but lost the contingent election in the Georgia General Assembly to Maddox.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] It was also the first time since 1916 that the Republican Party contested a gubernatorial election.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] If Callaway had won the contingent election or a majority of the popular vote, he would have become the only Republican governor of Georgia in the 20th century.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] As of 2022, this is the last time that Dougherty, Macon, Randolph, Richmond, Stewart, and Talbot counties voted for the Republican candidate for governor, and the last time that Liberty County did not vote for the Democratic candidate.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Former Governor Ernest Vandiver was considered the favorite to return to his former job (although governors could not then succeed themselves, they could run again after leaving office), but he dropped out of the race because of health problems.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] That opened the door for former Governor Ellis Arnall, former Lieutenant Governor Garland T.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Byrd, state Senator Jimmy Carter, and two segregationist businessmen, Lester Maddox and James H.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray Sr., to run for the Democratic nomination.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray, a Massachusetts native, publisher of the *Albany Herald* and founder of what is now Gray Television, was a former Georgia Democratic state chairman who defended segregation in his northern accent before the 1960 Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] In the primary race, Maddox had often called upon Gray to leave the race, having said that his opponent was "going down like the *Titanic*".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray remained in the race and finished fourth in the primary.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] He declared neutrality in the Maddox-Arnall runoff election, not openly supporting either candidate.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] However, one of Gray's associates, Roy V.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Harris of Augusta, a member of the Georgia State Board of Regents, supported Maddox over Arnall.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray supporters attempted to entice Maddox to leave the race with a $100,000 payment.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Gray denied involvement in the scheme but would not, on Maddox's request, take a lie detector test.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The primary was held on September 13, 1966.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Pursuant to Georgia law, as no candidate received a majority of votes in the primary, a runoff was held on September 27.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Smith was the Democratic nominee for Lieutenant Governor of Georgia, after he defeated incumbent Peter Zack Geer in the primary.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] He was the first Republican Representative from Georgia since Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] No other Republicans sought down-ballot constitutional offices.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] State Senator Holden Eugene "Gene" Sanders of DeKalb County, a moderate Republican, sought to run for lieutenant governor, but Callaway said that Sanders did not follow the proper procedures.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The Republican strategy was to shun all other statewide races for fear that a full ticket would unify the Democrats.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The *Atlanta Journal*, which ultimately endorsed Callaway, claimed that key Republicans were a clique who hoped to build the party from the governor's office.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The *Athens Daily News* depicted traditional Georgia Republican leaders as "would-be politicians [who viewed the party as] personal property and who made no real effort to expand into a broad-based and effective political organization".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Some people were unhappy with both major nominees and took the "Go Bo" of Callaway's campaign, expanding it to "Go Bo, and take Lester with you".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Under Georgia law at the time, the Georgia General Assembly would be required to hold a contingent election if no candidate received a majority of the popular vote.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Persons opposed to the contingent election procedure filed an action in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia, contending that a contingent election would violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The three-judge federal district court declared the Georgia contingent procedure unconstitutional and void on November 17, 1966, but less than a month later, on December 12, 1966, the United States Supreme Court reversed, and the contingent election went forward.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1966-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Maddox was elected on the first ballot despite losing the popular vote by 0.31%.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The **1967 Tanana Valley Flood** or **1967 Fairbanks Flood** was a severe flood that affected east-central Alaska in August 1967.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The city of Fairbanks, nearby Fort Wainwright, and Nenana saw record breaking water levels and widespread damage.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Flooding was recorded over a large swath of the state, from Eagle on the east to Ruby on the west.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Many major tributaries to the Yukon River saw flooding, including the Salcha, Chatanika, Tolovana, lower Tanana, and Birch Creek rivers.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The worst flooding occurred in the White Mountains northeast of Fairbanks, although this area is sparsely populated.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] All of Fairbanks was flooded, and more than 12,000 people were evacuated.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Fairbanks and Nenana were declared national disaster areas.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Six deaths were reported, along with damage exceeding $170 million.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Due to repeated previous flood damage, the community of Minto relocated nearly 20 miles north after this flood.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] As a result of the flood and to help prevent further disasters, stream and precipitation gauges were installed in the Chena River basin to monitor water levels.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Congress also approved the National Flood Insurance Act of 1968, authorizing the building of the Chena River Lakes Flood Control Project, which includes the Moose Creek Dam, the Tanana River Levee, and various drainage channels.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Historically, the Tanana River saw varied rates of flooding.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Sediment studies at Luke's Slough, which is about 9 miles southwest of Fairbanks, show that between 1000 AD and 0 AD, flooding was relatively common.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] After that, floods were rare until around the 1500s.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] In the last 400 years, there were only three major floods in the sediment record, with a recurrence interval of 125 years.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] On average, Fairbanks receives just over 11 inches of precipitation, either as rain or water equivalent.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Roughly half of this is received from June through September as rain.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] By month, the averages are 1.39 inches for June, 1.84 inches for July, 2.20 inches for August, and 1.10 inches for September.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Other months receive less than a water equivalent inch.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Fairbanks and nearby communities were established and expanded on the Tanana River floodplain and there were at least 15 serious floods recorded that happened in the area.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The floodplain experiences two kinds of flooding, one from spring breakup and the other from short duration heavy rainfall in the summer.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Major spring flooding from ice jams occurred in 1905, 1911, 1937 and 1948.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Rain produced flooding happened only in August 1930 before the 1967 flood.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The majority of the flood risk in the Fairbanks area is due to spring break up.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] However, ice jam flooding in the region is usually restricted, while rain-caused flooding affects a much larger area.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] As early as 1930, residents of Fairbanks expressed concern about flooding from the Tanana River.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Before 1945, a channel called Chena Slough branched off of the main channel of the Tanana River, and indicated that the Tanana River might be establishing its main channel further north upstream of Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Starting in July, a low north of Alaska and a high in the north Pacific set up a pattern of increased precipitation so that Fairbanks received over 3 inches of rain for the month.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] In August, a large scale pattern brought arctic air from the northwest of Alaska and increased winds from the southwest.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] This was in part due to the remnants of Tropical Storm Hope and an arctic front west of Fairbanks that brought in an atmospheric river from the Pacific on 8–11 August.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] On 12 August, weather conditions were similar to those found in squall lines in the Great Plains of the United States.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] From the 13th onwards, a low pressure system from Bristol Bay brought even more precipitation into the area.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Rain was concentrated around central to eastern Interior Alaska, with much comparatively milder rainfall values in the Alaska Range and Denali National Park.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Significant rainfall occurred from 8 August and lasted until around 20 August, although it was variable at times.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] At the Fairbanks International Airport, a record breaking 6.15 inches of rain was reported between 8 and 15 August.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] On the 13th, the daily record of rain at the Fairbanks Airport was broken, with 3.61 inches of observed rain, which is still the highest daily total for that station.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Between 10 and 15 August, several areas of heavy rain were recorded, as much as 7.18 inches just north of Talkeetna.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The flood was the worst disaster in Fairbanks' history.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Roughly 95% of Fairbanks was flooded, and the flood water's depth reached a maximum of 5 feet.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Nearly every house received water damage, and there was at least an inch of brown mud on every submerged surface.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The cost of damage in Fairbanks alone was estimated to be $85 million.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The Richardson Highway was washed out near Salcha for about half a mile.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Upstream from Fairbanks there were numerous landslides caused by heavy rain, and several stream gauges were destroyed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Chena Hot Springs road also suffered washouts.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Nenana received widespread damage and was the only other community besides Fairbanks that had a population of over 300 at the time.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Flooding was caused by both the Nenana and Tanana rivers.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Estimated damages for Nenana ranged about $1 million.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Damage was reported by boaters along Birch Creek near Circle and a stream gauge within the Birch Creek basin was destroyed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The Steese Highway going to Circle was heavily damaged, both near Circle and along the Chatanika River corridor.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Downriver from Nenana, the Tolovana River contributed to flooding, causing damage along the Elliot Highway.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Other damage included rural areas and the Alaska Railroad, valued at $7 million.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Although flood control legislation was enacted in 1958, this flood brought new urgency.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] Congress approved the National Flood Insurance Act of 1968, and the Flood Control Act of 1958 gave the authority to build the Chena River Lakes Flood Control Project, which includes the Moose Creek Dam, the Tanana River Levee, and various drainage channels.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] In order to help prevent similar disasters, a network of precipitation and stream gauges was also installed along the Chena and Tanana river basins.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The community of Minto relocated from Old Minto to their current site in the years after this flood.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1967-fairbanks-flood] The severity of the flood of 1967 was so much higher in magnitude than any previously recorded flood that the frequency of such an event cannot be accurately.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The **1970 Georgia gubernatorial election** was held in the U.S. state on November 3, 1970.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] It was marked by the election as Governor of Georgia of the relatively little-known former state senator Jimmy Carter after a hard battle in the Democratic primary.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] This election is famous because Carter, who was often regarded as one of the New South Governors, later ran for president in 1976 on his gubernatorial record and won.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] As of 2026, this was the last time Fulton County was carried by the Republican candidate in a gubernatorial election, the only time it failed to back Carter, and the last time a Democrat in any race won without carrying it.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] It is also the last time that Clarke County voted for the Republican candidate for governor.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Under the Georgia constitution of 1945, incumbent Democratic governor Lester Maddox was prohibited from seeking re-election.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Initially the strongest candidate was former governor Carl E.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Sanders was a moderate, who worked to improve education, the environment and led the transition away from racial segregation with cooperation with the United States Federal Government.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] He left office at the peak of his popularity.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] His main opponent was former state senator and candidate for the gubernatorial nomination in 1966 Jimmy Carter.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Despite Sanders's initial front-runner status and popularity, Carter won by nearly 20 points.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Governor Maddox ran for lieutenant governor and won the nomination.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] At this time, Georgia was still regarded as a part of the Democratic Party's Solid South, despite the Republican plurality in the 1966 gubernatorial race.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic position in 1970 was again regarded as safe.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] TV newsman Hal Suit faced Comptroller James L.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Bentley, who had been elected as a Democrat but joined the Republican party in 1968.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] While he refused to join the segregationist White Citizens' Council, he ran a campaign specifically designed to win over the segregationist vote that had made Maddox governor four years earlier.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Carter's true feelings about race might be better indicated by the fact that his had been one of only two families which voted to admit blacks to the Plains Baptist Church, but that was not something advertised in the 1970 race for governor.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to this campaign, Jimmy Carter appeared to be a proponent of civil rights and desegregation.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] In 1954 he refused to join the White Citizens Council despite immense pressure and went on to vote against segregation for his church in 1965.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] However, after failing to run as a moderate in the Georgia Gubernatorial Election of 1966, Carter's new strategy in 1970 was designed to attract the pro-segregationist vote.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Poll data suggested that the appearance of a pro-segregationist position could be critical to winning the race, even if it was never overtly stated.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] In order to shore up segregationist support, Carter made overtures to numerous racial organizations, and even personally called the cofounder of the White Citizens Council.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Carter's apparent support for segregation sparked animosity with his opponent Carl Sanders.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Sanders claims that when his own campaign had presented the same poll data, he refused to pursue a strategy on it for moral reasons.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Furthermore, Carter's campaign printed numerous pamphlets insinuating Sanders was too "chummy" with Black Americans.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Ultimately, Carter himself has expressed embarrassment and regret over his strategy.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1970-georgia-gubernatorial-election] Carter won praise for his strategy from Leroy Johnson, who stated "I understand why he ran that kind of ultra-conservative campaign.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The **1972 Democratic National Convention** was the presidential nominating convention of the Democratic Party for the 1972 presidential election.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] It was held at Miami Beach Convention Center in Miami Beach, Florida, also the host city of the Republican National Convention that year, on July 10–13, 1972.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] O'Brien served as permanent chairman of the convention, while Yvonne Braithwaite Burke served as vice-chair, becoming the first African American and the first woman of color to hold that position.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] On the last day of the convention, Lawrence F.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] O'Brien departed and Burke was left to preside for about fourteen hours.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated Senator George McGovern of South Dakota for president and Senator Thomas Eagleton of Missouri for vice president.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Eagleton withdrew from the race just 19 days later after it was disclosed that he had previously undergone mental health treatment, including electroshock therapy, and he was replaced on the ballot by Sargent Shriver of Maryland, a Kennedy in-law.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which has been described as "a disastrous start to the general election campaign", was one of the most unusual—perhaps the most contentious in the history of the Democratic Party since 1924—with sessions beginning in the early evening and lasting until sunrise the next morning.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Previously excluded political activists gained influence at the expense of elected officials and traditional core Democratic constituencies such as organized labor.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] A protracted vice presidential nominating process delayed McGovern's acceptance speech (which he considered "the best speech of his life") until 2:48 a.m.—after most television viewers had gone to bed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The 1972 convention was significant as the first implementation of the reforms set by the Commission on Party Structure and Delegate Selection, which McGovern himself had chaired before deciding to run for president.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] After McGovern resigned from his position as chair, he was replaced as chair by U.S.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Representative Donald Fraser, which gave the McGovern–Fraser Commission its name.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The 28-member commission was established after the tumultuous 1968 convention.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] In addition, there were new rules ensuring that party meetings in non-rural areas were held on uniform dates, at uniform times, and in places of easy access and that adequate public notice of all party meetings concerned with delegate selection was posted.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Among the most significant of the changes were new quotas mandating that certain percentages of delegates be women or members of minority groups.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] As a result of the new rules, subjects that were previously deemed not fit for political debate, such as abortion and gay rights, now occupied the forefront of political discussion.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The new rules for choosing and seating delegates created an unusual number of rules and credentials challenges.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Many traditional Democratic groups such as organized labor and big-city political machines had small representation at the convention.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Many traditional Democratic leaders and politicians felt that McGovern's delegate count did not reflect the wishes of most Democratic voters.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Georgia Governor Jimmy Carter helped to spearhead a "Stop McGovern" campaign, while at the same time trying to become McGovern's candidate for vice president.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The stop-McGovern forces tried unsuccessfully to alter the delegate composition of the California delegation.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The Illinois primary required voters to select individual delegates, not presidential candidates.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Most Illinois delegation members were uncommitted and were controlled or influenced by Chicago Mayor Richard J.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Daley, the leader of the Chicago political machine.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The delegation was challenged by McGovern supporters arguing that the results of the primary did not create a diverse enough delegation in terms of women and minorities.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The credentials committee, headed by Patricia Roberts Harris, rejected the entire elected delegation, including elected women and minorities, and seated an unelected delegation led by Chicago Alderman William Singer and Jesse Jackson, pledged to George McGovern.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The California primary was "winner-take-all", which was contrary to the delegate selection rules.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] So even though McGovern only won the California primary by a 5% electoral margin, he won all 271 of their delegates to the convention.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The anti-McGovern group argued for a proportional distribution of the delegates, while the McGovern forces stressed that the rules for the delegate selection had been set and the Stop McGovern alliance was trying to change the rules after the game.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The credentials committee ruled in favor of the anti-McGovern group prior to the convention, leaving McGovern short of a first-ballot majority.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] However, the committee was overruled by a floor vote on the first day of the convention and a unanimous McGovern delegation was seated.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern recognized the mixed results of the changes that he made to the Democratic nominating convention, saying, "I opened the doors of the Democratic Party and 20 million people walked out".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The so-called "magic number", or number of delegates needed to secure the nomination, was 1,509.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Formed after "divisive platform battles", the 1972 Democratic National Convention's platform has been characterized as "probably the most liberal one ever adopted by a major party in the United States".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] It advocated immediate withdrawal from Vietnam, amnesty for war resisters, the abolition of the draft, a guaranteed job for all Americans (it offered to "make the government the employer of last resort"), and a guaranteed family income well above the poverty line.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The Feminist Movement was a major influence on the Democratic platform of 1972, and on the entire convention in general.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] With renewed vigor, the Democrats reaffirmed their dedication to the Equal Rights Amendment, as did the Republicans.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] There were disagreements within the Democrats of the National Women's Political Caucus (NWPC), and the Women's Movement in general, over how to best approach certain issues.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] At the convention Betty Friedan clashed with Gloria Steinem over the way NWPC women should approach certain issues, and whether or not they should make sure to throw all possible support behind Shirley Chisholm (both women were supporters of Chisholm's presidential campaign).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] As the convention was occurring on Miami Beach, Gloria Steinem chose The Betsy Ross Hotel as headquarters for the National Organization for Women (NOW).
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Built in 1942, the hotel had been named after Betsy Ross, the Philadelphia seamstress who sewed American Flags.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern ultimately excised the abortion issue from the party's platform; recent publications show McGovern was deeply conflicted on the issue.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Actress and activist Shirley MacLaine, though privately supporting abortion rights, urged the delegates to vote against the plank.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Germaine Greer flatly contradicted Steinem's account.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Having recently gained public notoriety for her feminist manifesto *The Female Eunuch* and sparring with Norman Mailer, Greer was commissioned to cover the convention for *Harper's Magazine*.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer criticized Steinem's "controlled jubilation" that 38% of the delegates were women, ignoring that "many delegations had merely stacked themselves with token females...The McGovern machine had already pulled the rug out from under them".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer leveled her most searing critique on Steinem for her capitulation on abortion rights.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer reported, "Jacqui Ceballos called from the crowd to demand abortion rights on the Democratic platform, but Bella [Abzug] and Gloria stared glassily out into the room", thus killing the abortion rights platform.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Greer asks, "Why had Bella and Gloria not helped Jacqui to nail him on abortion?
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] What reticence, what loserism had afflicted them?" The cover of *Harper's* that month read, "Womanlike, they did not want to get tough with their man, and so, womanlike, they got screwed".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] A coalition of gay rights groups at the convention "drew up a proposed platform provision that called for, among other things, repealing laws against homosexuals marrying".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The provision was rejected by a vote of 54–34.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Afterwards, however, two delegates, Jim Foster and Madeline Davis (the first openly lesbian delegate to a major national political convention), spoke publicly on its behalf.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The platform championed busing under its "Education" plank, stating, "Transportation of students is another tool to accomplish desegregation".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The McGovern platform is often criticized as a "reformist coup" responsible in large part for the subsequent decline in American liberalism and chasing away the Democratic Party's "best politicians".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] It alienated the "working- and lower-middle class voters [who] saw [the platform] as threatening to traditional, deeply valued, if inequitable social arrangements"—so much so that one in three Democrats voted for Nixon, the Republican incumbent, in the presidential election in November.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The Democrats also included "the right to be different" in their 1972 platform.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] According to the party, this right included the right to "maintain a cultural or ethnic heritage or lifestyle, without being forced into a compelled homogeneity".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Most polls showed McGovern running well behind incumbent President Richard Nixon, except when McGovern was paired with Massachusetts Senator Ted Kennedy.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern and his campaign brain trust lobbied Kennedy heavily to accept the bid to be McGovern's running mate, but he continually refused their advances, and instead suggested U.S.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Representative (and House Ways and Means Committee chairman) Wilbur Mills of Arkansas and Boston Mayor Kevin White.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Offers were then made to Hubert Humphrey, Connecticut Senator Abraham Ribicoff, and Minnesota Senator Walter Mondale, all of whom turned it down.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern and his campaign staff felt that a Kennedy-style figure was best to balance the ticket: a Catholic, big city-based leader with strong ties to organized labor and urban political machines.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Immediately, White was dropped from consideration.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Finally, the vice presidential slot was offered to Senator Thomas Eagleton of Missouri, who was relatively unknown to many of the delegates.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] By the time the roll call finally began, many of the delegates were angry and wary after the protracted infighting, and combined with the last-day-of-school atmosphere of the proceedings, caused the vice-presidential balloting to become nothing short of a farce.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The delegates cast ballots for a record 79 people, including many not involved in politics, as well as three deceased persons, Chinese leader Mao Zedong, and the fictional Archie Bunker.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] As the vote went on, Farenthold began to attract an unexpected level of support, eventually leading to something of a grassroots campaign to nominate her over Eagleton.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] However, this ultimately proved too late and too disorganized to have any serious chance of denying Eagleton the nomination.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Eventually, Eagleton secured the nomination at 1:40 a.m.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] This delay forced the acceptance speeches of the candidates to be given well past the television prime time hours, and probably hurt the McGovern campaign by not creating the so-called "convention bounce".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Several days after the convention, it was revealed that Senator Eagleton had been hospitalized for depression and had electric shock treatment, and was also rumored to be more than a social drinker.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern stood behind his choice and stated that he was behind Senator Eagleton "1000 percent".
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The news media and many political pros, especially in the Democratic Party, lobbied hard for his removal from the ticket.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Eventually, McGovern felt compelled to accept Senator Eagleton's withdrawal from the ticket.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] The episode had placed McGovern in a "no-win" situation: if he kept Eagleton, the selection did not look good for the decision-making ability of the McGovern team, while if he removed Eagleton, he appeared to be weak and vacillating.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] Since this incident, front-running presidential candidates have developed short lists of potential running mates, and have meticulously performed background checks.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1972-democratic-national-convention] McGovern chose Sargent Shriver as his running mate a few weeks later: the McGovern-Shriver ticket went on to win electoral votes in only Massachusetts and D.C., and lost the election to incumbents Richard Nixon and Spiro Agnew by the largest percentage of the vote since 1936.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The **1976 Democratic National Convention** met at Madison Square Garden in New York City, from July 12 to July 15, 1976.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The assembled United States Democratic Party delegates at the convention nominated former Governor Jimmy Carter of Georgia for president and Senator Walter Mondale of Minnesota for vice president.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] John Glenn and Barbara Jordan gave the keynote addresses.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] Jordan's keynote address made her the first African-American woman to deliver the keynote address at a Democratic National Convention.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The convention was the first in New York City since the 103-ballot 1924 convention.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] Carter easily won the nomination on the first ballot.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] He then chose Mondale, a liberal and a protégé of Hubert Humphrey, as his running mate.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] Mondale was put over the top at roll call by the convention's second youngest delegate Cathy Clardy who cast the delegate votes for the State of Minnesota.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The Carter–Mondale ticket went on to win the 1976 presidential election on November 2.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The convention is also notable for the fact that congresswoman Lindy Boggs, who presided over it, thus became the first woman to preside over a national political convention.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The Democrats' 1976 platform called for continued price controls on natural gas, a policy which had caused dwindling domestic natural gas reserves since 1974 and which President Gerald Ford was asking to rescind.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] Despite an address from anti-abortion activist Erma Clardy Craven, the platform added "it is undesirable to attempt to amend the U.S.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] The following people had their names placed in nomination.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] According to Jimmy Carter, his top choices for vice president were: Walter Mondale, Edmund Muskie, Frank Church, Adlai Stevenson III, John Glenn, and Henry M.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/1976-democratic-national-convention] In his acceptance speech, Mondale diverted from his printed text which echoed John F.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] The **Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act** (**ANILCA**) is a United States federal law signed by President Jimmy Carter on December 2, 1980.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] ANILCA provided varying degrees of special protection to over 157 million acres (640,000 km2) of land, including national parks, national wildlife refuges, national monuments, wild and scenic rivers, recreational areas, national forests, and conservation areas.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] It was, and remains to date, the single largest expansion of protected lands in history and more than doubled the size of the National Park System.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] In 1971, the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) was signed into law to resolve the long-standing issues surrounding aboriginal land claims in Alaska, as well as to stimulate economic development throughout Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] These lands, referred to as "d-2" lands, were to be available for potential congressional designation as National Parks, Wildlife Refuges, Wild and Scenic rivers, or National Forests.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] The "d-2" provision of ANCSA gave the Secretary nine months to withdraw lands before they would re-open to development.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] As stated, the "d-2" provision of ANCSA set a deadline for the Secretary to withdraw lands within nine months of the passage of ANCSA.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] On January 29, 1973, Congressman James A.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Haley (D-Florida) introduced the Morton proposal as H.R.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] 12336, and the next day Senator Henry M.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Jackson (D-Washington) introduced the Senate version of the bill.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] These bills were the first of many failed proposals leading to the eventual passage of ANILCA seven years later.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Over the course of the seven years many bills were introduced with a wide range of proposals for disposal of the selected lands.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] As the sunset date approached in 1978 both chambers of Congress scrambled to pass a bill.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] 39 was passed by the House of Representatives.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] 39 was referred to the Senate Committee on Energy and Natural Resources for mark up and combined with a number of other bills pertaining to Alaska lands.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Senator Ted Stevens (R-Alaska) was instrumental in making significant changes to the original House resolution.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] The final bill submitted by the Senate energy committee was deemed unacceptable by the Carter administration and supporters of H.R.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] With limited time left before adjournment, the House and Senate conferenced in order to resolve differences between the two bills.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Senator Mike Gravel (D-Alaska) inserted himself into the negotiations, making a number of new demands not included in either bill.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Changes made to the bill did not satisfy Gravel, and he refused to support the bill.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] With adjournment fast approaching, a provision to extend the (d)(2) protections for one more year to allow for additional time to pass a bill was passed in the House, and introduced in the Senate on October 16, 1978.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Gravel threatened a filibuster, and the provision did not pass the Senate.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] The sunset provision of section (d)(2) of ANCSA was set to expire on December 18, 1978.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] President Carter used the Antiquities Act to designate 56 million acres (230,000 km2) as 17 National Monuments by executive order on December 1, 1978.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Much of the lands designated as National Monument were part of the original Morton Proposal.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] An additional 40 million acres (160,000 km2) were withdrawn under the authority of section 204(c) of the Federal Land Policy and Management Act by Interior Secretary Cecil Andrus.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Carter stated that he had been forced to use the Antiquities Act by Congress's failure to act in a reasonable time, but his actions nevertheless caused wide protest across Alaska.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] President Carter was burned in effigy in Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Residents in the Cantwell area undertook a large act of civil disobedience known as the *Great Denali Trespass* – they went into the park, fired off guns, made campfires, and conducted various other activities prohibited under Federal regulations.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] The towns of Eagle and Glennallen, both in the shadow of new monuments, produced official proclamations stating that the towns would not support NPS authorities, not enforce NPS regulations, and would shelter individuals who broke the regulations.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Though these protests continued for some time, the designation of the monuments broke the legislative opposition to ANILCA.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Some in Congress, and various oil and gas industry, and other development interest, continued to oppose passage of the bill, but in the wake of Carter's proclamations most opponents recognized the need to work toward passage of an acceptable bill, rather than no bill at all.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] However, in 1978, 75 seats in the House had changed hands, producing a much more conservative body than the one that had supported Carter's use of the Antiquities Act.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Proponents were forced to continue to work compromises, and the bill's passage was further delayed.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] In early November 1980, Jimmy Carter lost re-election to Ronald Reagan, and the Republican Party won a majority of seats in the Senate.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Conservationists and other proponents of the legislation recognized that if they did not accept the compromise then on the table, they would be forced to begin again in the next Congress with decidedly less support.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] The bill was passed in late November, and signed into law by President Carter in December.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Senator Gravel, meanwhile, took considerable blame in Alaska for forcing Carter's hand with the Antiquities Act.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Though Carter was hardly held blameless for the creation of the new national monuments, Gravel was taken to task for the unpopular decision as well and was denied his party's nomination for his Senate seat in the 1980 election.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] A telephone poll in 2000 showed that 45 percent of Alaskans supported the protection of the ANILCA-designated 1002 coastal plain area of the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, the most controversial aspect of ANILCA's protected areas, while 49 percent opposed the protection.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] This was the price conservationists paid in the compromise.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] Under Title VIII, Subsistence Management And Use, not just Alaska Natives qualified but also rural residents were granted hunting and fishing rights when fish and game are not under outside threat.
[src:alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act/alaska-national-interest-lands-conservation-act] In addition the bill expedited the enactment of the 1971 Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act.
